        dict({
          'content': '''
            Here’s a CLV segmentation and churn-risk view built from invoices in the Chinook database.
            
            How it’s calculated
            - Lifetime value (LTV): sum of all invoice totals per customer.
            - Orders: count of invoices per customer; AOV: average invoice total.
            - Days since last purchase: max(0, today − last invoice date). Future-dated invoices are treated as 0 days.
            - LTV segments (percentile-based): 
              - High: top ~20% by LTV
              - Medium: next ~30%
              - Low: bottom ~50%
              - No Spend: LTV = 0
            - Churn risk:
              - Active: 0–90 days
              - Low Risk: 91–180 days
              - Medium Risk: 181–365 days
              - High Risk: >365 days
              - Churn Risk: No purchases (never bought)
            
            Churn-risk summary (all 59 customers)
            - High Risk: 7 customers | Avg LTV: 38.05 | Avg days since last purchase: 415.3
            - Medium Risk: 12 customers | Avg LTV: 38.70 | Avg days since last purchase: 266.0
            - Low Risk: 8 customers | Avg LTV: 41.12 | Avg days since last purchase: 125.0
            - Active: 32 customers | Avg LTV: 39.65 | Avg days since last purchase: 16.5
            
            Top high-risk customers to prioritize (longest time since last purchase)
            - Puja Srivastava (India) — LTV 36.64 — 474 days — LV segment: Low — Churn risk: High
            - Niklas Schröder (Germany) — LTV 37.62 — 443 days — LV segment: Low — Churn risk: High
            - Leonie Köhler (Germany) — LTV 37.62 — 430 days — LV segment: Low — Churn risk: High
            - Jack Smith (USA) — LTV 39.62 — 412 days — LV segment: Medium — Churn risk: High
            - Dominique Lefebvre (France) — LTV 38.62 — 399 days — LV segment: Medium — Churn risk: High
            - Mark Taylor (Australia) — LTV 37.62 — 381 days — LV segment: Low — Churn risk: High
            - Tim Goyer (USA) — LTV 38.62 — 368 days — LV segment: Medium — Churn risk: High
            
            Notes and next steps
            - The percent-rank approach keeps LTV segments relative to your customer base. As spending patterns shift, segment thresholds adjust automatically.
            - If you want fixed-dollar LTV segments (e.g., Low < $30, Medium $30–$45, High > $45) or different churn thresholds, say the word and I’ll rerun the analysis.
            - I can export the full customer-level table (customer, country, LTV, orders, AOV, last purchase date, days since last purchase, LTV segment, churn risk) as CSV if needed.
          ''',
